Clustering using uncentered correlation and average linkage - declare a function for uncentered distance using cosange

#cosangle function
uncenter.dist<-function(m) {
  as.dist(as.matrix(distancematrix(m, d="cosangle")))
}

In this fully clustered HCA heatmap, the distance metric is Euclidean, and the agglomeration clustering algorithm is uncentered correlation with average linkage.

row.clus<-hclust(uncenter.dist(data.scale), method = "ave")
col.clus<-hclust(uncenter.dist(t(data.scale)), method = "ave")

Heatmap(data.scale, name = "mtcars heatmap", 
        cluster_rows=row.clus, cluster_columns=col.clus)

## Research Proposal

Purpose of this study

The purpose of this study is to use a cluster analysis heatmap to create a descriptive analysis of summer programming types attended by Asian and Hispanic students between 1st and 2nd grade. By examining the kinds of outside-of-school activities these students engage in outside of the traditional classroom, this study seeks to uncover participation patterns that could possibly highlight disparities in access to summer programming opportunities. With the field of educations current emphasis on closing equity gaps, this study will explore whether Asian and Hispanic students have distinct patterns in summer programming participation.

Research literature on this topic

There is promising evidence in the literature that summer enrichment programs can lead to improved academic outcomes and enhanced social skills among low-income students (Augustine et al., 2016). These programs can also enhance students critical thinking and professional skills, as evidenced by research indicating that hands-on experiences during summer learning can positively influence students academic trajectories (Hernandez-Matias et al., 2019).

However, disparities in access and participation in these enrichment activities are prevalent across various demographic groups. McCombs et al.highlight that summer programs can mitigate learning loss and promote positive outcomes, particularly for low-income students who lack access to enriching activities during this period (McCombs et al., 2020). Atterberry and McEachin further emphasize the role of summer in understanding achievement disparities, noting that students from lower socioeconomic backgrounds experience greater learning loss during the summer compared to their more affluent peers (Atteberry & McEachin, 2020). This phenomenon is often referred to as the summer slide, where students lose academic skills over the break, a trend that disproportionately affects those already at a disadvantage (Dresden, 2019). The evidence suggests that targeted summer interventions can help bridge these gaps, yet participation remains uneven across demographic lines (Davies et al., 2022). The impact of summer programming on academic achievement is further illustrated by Kuhfield et al., who analyzed racial and ethnic disparities in learning and found that achievement gaps can shrink during summer months when students engage in structured activities (Kuhfeld et al., 2020).

Citations

Why use a cluster analysis heatmap?

Using a cluster analysis heatmap for this study will allow for visual groupings of participation types based on observed similarities and differences, capturing the diversity within and across student groups. Cluster analysis heatmaps are well-suited for descriptive analysis as it may reveal patterns that might otherwise go unnoticed in traditional tabular analysis. This approach will enable us to visually distinguish patterns of participation for Asian and Hispanic students, potentially identifying clusters based on demographics, socio-economic characteristics, and participation in specific program types. ### Research Questions What types of summer programming do Asian and Hispanic students participate in? How do demographic and socio-economic factors influence participation patterns in summer programs? To what extent do participation patterns represent academic outcomes the following school year? ### Data Source This study will utilize the ECLS-K:2011 (Early Childhood Longitudinal Study, Kindergarten Class of 2010-11) dataset from the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES). This public-use data set contains detailed information on students from kindergarten through fifth grade including demographics, family background, and educational outcomes. This dataset also includes responses from parents about childrens participation in summer activities, making it well-suited for this analysis. Key variables for clustering include summer programming types, demographics (such as Age, ethnicity, and language spoken at home), socio-economic factors (such as family income, SES, and parental occupation prestige scores), and behavioral and educational outcomes for the Fall semester after the summer. ### Clustering Approach and Generalized Equation For this study, agglomerative hierarchical clustering will be used, applying an uncensored correlation distance measure. Agglomerative clustering will start by treating each student as an individual cluster and gradually merge the clusters based on similarity until an optimal number of clusters is achieved. The uncentered correlation distance will be used to measure the similarity, the equation for this distance measure is represented below: The distance measure of uncentered correlation is represented below (Bowers, 2010, p.18)

\[r(x_i, y_i) = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i}{\sigma_{x}^{(0)}} \right) \left( \frac{y_i}{\sigma_{y}^{(0)}} \right)\] where \[\sigma_x^{(0)}= \sqrt{ \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( x_i \right) ^2}\] \[\sigma_y^{(0)}= \sqrt{ \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( y_i \right) ^2}\]

The average distance between the total number of cases in both clusters, nAnB, between the total number of cases in cluster A, nA, and the total number of cases in cluster B, nB, is then used to determine the distance between any two clusters, A and B (Bowers, 2010, p.18). This is represented by:

\[D(A,B)=\frac{1}{n_An_B} \sum_{i=1}^{n_A} \sum_{i=1}^{n_B} r(x_i,y_i)\]

Bowers, A. J., (2010) Analyzing the longitudinal K-12 grading histories of entire cohorts of students: Grades, data driven decision making, dropping out and hierarchical cluster analysis, Practical Assessment, Research, and Evaluation 15(1): 7. doi: https://doi.org/10.7275/r4zq-9c31 ### Hypothesis It hypothesized that Asian students may participate more frequently in academic and music programs than Hispanic students. Additionally, students from higher SES backgrounds may show higher participation rates across program types due to greater resource availability. ### Implications for this Research By providing a clearer picture of summer program engagement, this study can inform those in decision making positions to decrease opportunity and access gaps to summer programming. Ultimately, ever so slightly enhance educational equity across socio-economic and ethnic lines.

uncenter.dist<-function(m) {
  as.dist(as.matrix(distancematrix(m, d="cosangle")))
}

row.clus<-hclust(uncenter.dist(song_scale), method = "ave")
col.clus<-hclust(uncenter.dist(t(song_scale)), method = "ave")

        cluster_rows=row.clus, cluster_columns=col.clus,

        row_title = "Song",
       row_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 5))
